Categorical handedness (primary)

Summary

For reaction time, LVF global>local bias was significantly reduced in left handers ( = 331, EHI <= -40) compared to right handers (= 378, EHI >= +40; difference between groups = 11.67ms, 95% CI [0.65, 22.69], \(\chi^2(1)\) = 4.31, = .038, two-sided). Both groups showed significant LVF global>local bias: for right handers, the effect size was 27.31ms (95% CI [19.78, 34.83],(85,499.1) = 7.11, = < .0001, two-sided); for left handers, 15.64ms (95% CI [7.60, 23.69], (85,499.4) = 3.81, = .001, two-sided).

Within the local level, right and left handers showed reversed hemifield bias, in the direction predicted by AAH: right handers responded faster to local stimuli in the RVF than LVF by 12.28ms (95% CI [6.93, 17.63], (85,499.3) = 4.50, < .0001, two-sided), whereas left handers responded faster to local stimuli in the LVF than RVF by 9.65ms (95% CI [3.91, 15.39], (85,499.7 = 3.30, = .001, two-sided; difference = 21.94ms, 95% CI [14.01, 29.79], (85,499.5) = 5.48, < .0001, two-sided).

Stats

Reaction time is modeled as a linear effect of field, level, and handedness, using data from every target-present trial with a “go” response:

lmer( rt ~ field*level*handedness + (1 | subject) )

Plots

Diamonds and lineranges show mixed-effects model point estimates and 95% CI.


Categorical handedness (exploratory - EHI +/-100)

Summary

Limiting analysis to strong left and right handers with EHI scores of +/-100, left handers’ LVF>RVF global bias was reduced by 23.52ms (95% CI [7.10, 39.93], \(\chi^2(1)\) = 7.89, = .005, two-sided). Strong right handers showed significant LVF>RVF global bias (28.10ms, 95% CI [17.34, 38.86], (38,617.45) = 5.12, < .0001, two-sided); whereas strong left handers showed no significant interaction of field by level (4.59ms, 95% CI [-7.81, 16.98], (38,617.6) = 0.73, = .47, two-sided).

Within the local level, strong right and left handers showed reversed hemifield bias: right handers responded faster to local stimuli in the RVF than LVF by 13.56ms (95% CI [5.90, 21.22], (38,617.6) = 3.47, = .0005, two-sided), whereas left handers responded faster to local stimuli in the LVF than RVF by 18.09ms (95% CI [9.25, 26.93], (38,617.69) = 4.01 < .0001, two-sided; difference = 31.65ms, 95% CI [19.96, 43.35], (38,617.67) = 5.30, < .0001, two-sided).

Plots

Categorical handedness (exploratory - shape)

Summary

Some pilot participants reported that the circle targets were relatively easy to see compared to the square targets, and indeed, reaction times were faster for circles than for squares, at both the local level (difference = 66.71ms, 95% CI [62.81, 70.61], (85,494.1) = 14.49, < .0001, two-sided) and the global level (difference = 28.36ms, 95% CI [24.53, 32.20], (85,491.0) = 14.49, < .0001, two-sided). Because global precedence effects may be stronger under perceptual uncertainty , the circles’ high visibility could lead to lower global precedence, and potentially weaken the interaction of field by level. Indeed, participants showed greater global precedence for squares, by 40.68ms for right handers (95% CI [33.21, 48.15], (85,492.1) = 10.67, < .0001, two-sided), and 36.01ms for left handers (95% CI [28.01, 44.00], (85,492.9) = 8.83, < .001, two-sided). Within right handers, the interaction of field by level was greater for squares (37.66ms, 95% CI [26.97, 48.34], (85,491.4) = 6.91, < .0001, two-sided) than for circles (18.14ms, 95% CI [7.70, 28.58], (85,490.6) = 3.41, = .0007, two-sided; difference = 19.52ms, 95% CI [4.58, 34.46], (85,490.9) = 2.56, = .01, two-sided).

Though target shape did not have a significant effect on the interaction of field by level by handedness (15.89ms greater for squares, 95% CI [-5.99, 37.76], \(\chi^2(1)\) = 2.03, = .16, two-sided), the interaction of field by level by handedness was significant for squares (19.76ms, 95% CI [4.11, 35.40], (85,491.5) = 2.48, = .013, two-sided), but not for circles (3.87ms, 95% CI [-11.41, 19.16], (85,490.62) = 0.50, = .62,two-sided).

lmer( rt ~ field * level * handedness * shape + (1 | subject) )

Continuous handedness (primary)

Summary

With handedness treated as continuous, left handedness predicted reduced LVF global>local bias (0.067ms per EHI unit, 95% CI [0.003, 0.130], \(\chi^2(1)\) = 4.25, = .039, two-sided). Estimated LVF global>local bias for EHI +100 (strong right handers) was 28.14ms (95% CI [20.31, 35.98]), and for EHI -100 (strong left handers), 14.82ms (95% CI [6.48, 23.17]), a difference of 13.32ms.

Within the local level, left handedness predicted reversed RVF bias (0.123ms per EHI unit, 95% CI [0.078, 0.168], (101,766.6) = 5.34, = < .0001, two-sided). Strong right handers (EHI = +100) showed estimated RVF bias of 14.96ms (95% CI [9.38, 20.53]), and strong left handers (EHI = -100) showed estimated LVF bias of 9.61ms (95% CI [-1.88, 8.43]), a difference of 24.57ms.

Model RT as a linear effect of field, level, and EHI (continuous):

rt_model_ehi <- lmer( rt ~ field*level*ehi + (1 | subject) )
